  <h3>Why floating-point equality fails for money</h3>
  <p>
    JavaScript Numbers are IEEE-754 binary floating-point values. They represent fractions as sums of powers of two.
    Many simple decimal fractions such as 0.1, 0.99, 4.99 cannot be represented exactly as a finite sum of powers of two.
    So when you write 4.99 in code, the actual stored value is the nearest representable binary approximation (something like 4.990000000000000213...). When you add numbers or compare them with ===, those tiny differences matter. Two results that print as "14.98" might not have identical binary representations, so === returns false.
  </p>
