Explanation (concise):
- Why it fails: JavaScript Number uses binary floating point; many decimal fractions (0.1, 0.01, 4.99) cannot be exactly represented in binary, causing tiny rounding errors. When you add or compare floats, these tiny errors can make equality checks fail or totals look wrong.
- Why the fixed method works: representing amounts as whole cents (integers) avoids fractional binary representations entirely. Integer addition/comparison is exact. Store cents in your business logic and only format for display.
- Alternatives: use a decimal arithmetic library (decimal.js, Big.js) or use BigInt with scaled integers; for many apps storing cents as integers is simplest and efficient.

Try the sample buttons: add "4.99" and then "0.01" in the broken cart to see (4.99 + 0.01) !== 5.00, while the fixed cart will show exact cents 499 + 1 = 500 → $5.00.

