    <p>
      JavaScript Numbers are IEEE‑754 binary floating-point. Not all decimal fractions (like 0.99) have an exact binary representation.
      When you write 4.99 it becomes a binary approximation. Adding many such approximations can accumulate tiny errors,
      and strict equality (===) may fail because the in-memory binary value isn't exactly the decimal you typed.
    </p>
    <p>
      Example: 0.1 + 0.2 === 0.3 is false in JS. Similarly, summing 4.99 multiple times may produce 14.969999999999999 rather than 14.97.
      Using integer cents (4.99 -> 499 cents) avoids these binary-fraction representation issues because integers are exact.
